1 - Unemployment rate in Europe¶

[source: eurostat]

By having a look at eurostat, we can find a file that seems perfect following this path :

Database by theme >> Population and social conditions Labour market >> Employment and unemployment >> LFS series - detailed quarterly survey results (from 1998 onwards) >> Total unemployment - LFS series >> lfsq_urgan.

It contains the unemployment rates by country of the two first quarters of 2017.

We manually downloaded the data (as a .tsv file ('tab-separated values'))

In [3]:
data = pd.DataFrame.from_csv('./lfsq_urgan.tsv', sep='\t')
data = data.reset_index()

Here is a preview of what the data looks like:

We see that the first column groups multiple features together: 'unit', 'sex', 'age', 'citizen' and 'geo'. Therefore, we split it into multiple columns so that each feature can be handled more easily. We then reorder the columns by moving the new columns to the front of the dataframe, so that reading is easier.

In [5]:
#split the first column into 5 separate columns
data['unit'],data['sex'],data['age'],data['citizen'],data['geo'] = data[data.columns[0]].str.split(',').str

#drop the previous column
data = data.drop(data.columns[0], axis=1)

#reorder the columns
columns = data.columns.tolist()
columns = columns[-5:] + columns[:-5]

data = data[columns]

For our analysis, we choose to consider entries with an age interval of 'Y20-64': before 20 years, most people have not worked yet and are not considered as unemployed, and around 64, people start to retire or have already.

When considering the country of citizenship ('citizen'), we will use the entries having the value 'TOTAL'.

In [8]:
print(data['citizen'].unique())

['EU15_FOR' 'EU27_FOR' 'EU28_FOR' 'FOR' 'NAT' 'NEU15_FOR' 'NEU27_FOR'
 'NEU28_FOR' 'NRP' 'TOTAL']

Each entry also specifies whether it applies to 'Female' ('F'), 'Male' ('M') or 'Total' ('T').

In [9]:
print(data['sex'].unique())

['F' 'M' 'T']

We will only consider entries with the 'T' value, which regroups the percentages for both men and women.

Next we filter the data by keeping only the entries we are interested in:

In [10]:
datafilter = data[(data['age']=='Y20-64') 
                & (data['citizen']=='TOTAL') 
                & (data['sex']=='T') ].copy()
                                                                          
#convert to numeric  
datafilter.rename(columns = {'2017Q2 ':'2017Q2'}, inplace=True)
datafilter['2017Q2'] = pd.to_numeric(datafilter['2017Q2'],errors='coerce')
# keep not null
datafilter = datafilter[datafilter['2017Q2'].notnull()]
#remove the global data on europe
datafilter = datafilter[~(datafilter['geo'].str.startswith('EU') | datafilter['geo'].str.startswith('EA'))]

The topojson/europe.topojson.json overlay uses the international ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 convention. However, there are two countries whose 2-letter european country code differ from this alpha-2 convention: Greece and the United Kingdom, which are mapped to 'EL' and 'UK' instead of 'GR' and 'GB' respectively. We map them to the ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 convention, because this is the one used ini the topojson/europe.topojson.json.

note: the european convention uses the native name of the country for assigning the country code, not the english one.

In [13]:
datafilter.loc[datafilter['geo']=='UK', 'geo'] = 'GB'
datafilter.loc[datafilter['geo']=='EL', 'geo'] = 'GR'

We do not keep the countries in the json overlay for which we do not have any data from Eurostat (e.g. Azerbaijan, Monaco, Russia, ...), because we do not want them to get displayed on the map.

In [14]:
with open(state_geo_path) as json_data:
    europe_topojson = json.load(json_data)

#access the list of countries in the json
europe_topojson_list = europe_topojson['objects']['europe']['geometries']

#get the country codes in the eurostat data (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 convention)
european_country_codes = datafilter['geo'].unique()

#filter out the countries whose country code to not appear in the eurostat country codes
non_eurostat_countries = [c for c in europe_topojson_list if (c['id'] not in european_country_codes)]
eurostat_topojson_list = [c for c in europe_topojson_list if c not in non_eurostat_countries]

#assign the updated country list to the new json overlay
eurostat_topojson = europe_topojson
eurostat_topojson['objects']['europe']['geometries'] = eurostat_topojson_list

Observations¶

We displayed the unemployment rate of the second quarter of 2017. sEurostat define the unemployemnt as follows (Commission Regulation (EC) No 1897/2000 for more detail):

  1. In accordance with the ILO standards adopted by the 13th and 14th International Conference of Labour Statisticians (ICLS), for the purposes of the Community labour force sample survey, unemployed persons comprise persons aged 15 to 74 who were:

    • (a) without work during the reference week, i.e. neither had a job nor were at work (for one hour or more) in paid employment or self-employment;
    • (b) currently available for work, i.e. were available for paid employment or self-employment before the end of the two weeks following the reference week;
    • (c) actively seeking work, i.e. had taken specific steps in the four week period ending with the reference week to seek paid employment or self-employment or who found a job to start later, i.e. within a period of at most three months

Unfortunately, for built-in colour scales, Folium limits the range to 6 colours. This can be misleading: for instance, the map suggests that Italy, Spain, Grece and Croatia have the same unemployment rate, which is not the case.

In [19]:
datafilter[datafilter['geo'].isin(['GR', 'IT', 'ES', 'HR'])][['2017Q2','geo']]
Out[19]:
2017Q2 geo
24649 21.1 GR
24650 16.9 ES
24656 10.9 HR
24660 10.9 IT

Italy and Croatia have an unemployment rate near the lower limit of the scale (10%), whereas Greece and Spain have a much higher unemployment rate, near the top limit of the scale. Using quartile scale is a practical way to see variations between the different countries, although it may not show in an obvious manner if there are some outliers or not.

In any case, the map shows that the countries of southern europe have the highest unemployment rate.

With this map, Switzerland seems to stand somewhere below the mean of european countries. A quick numerical check confirms this observation:

In [20]:
print('Switzerland\'s unemployment rate: {0:.4f} %'.format(datafilter[datafilter['geo']=='CH']['2017Q2'].values[0]))
print('Average unemployment rate: {0:.4f} %'.format(datafilter['2017Q2'].mean()))

Switzerland's unemployment rate: 4.5000 %
Average unemployment rate: 7.6061 %

Observations¶

It is in Romandy (also known as the French-speaking Switzerland), that the unemployment rate tends to be the highest.

Now, we will slightly change the way we count unemployed individuals: we will not take into account those which already have a job and are looking for a new one ('Demandeurs d'emploi non chmeurs'), but only those who are looking for a job and have currently none ('Chmeurs inscrits').

note: in the amstat file, 'Chmeurs inscrits' + 'Demandeurs d'emploi non chmeurs' = 'Demandeurs d'emploi'

The amstat institution defines the unemployment rate as:

Nombre de chmeurs inscrits au jour de rfrence (dernier jour du mois) divis par le nombre de personnes actives, multipli par 100. Le nombre des personnes actives est recens chaque anne par lOffice fdral de la statistique dans le cadre du relev structurel (recensement de la population). Il slve, depuis le 1er janvier 2014, 4'493'249 personnes daprs le pooling de trois ans des donnes rcoltes dans le cadre des relevs structurels de 2012 2014. Le nombre des personnes actives utilis par le SECO comprend aussi les diplomates et fonctionnaires internationaux domicilis en Suisse. (from https://www.amstat.ch/v2/definition.jsp?lang=fr)

Registered unemployed individuals ("chmeurs inscrits") are defined as:

Personnes annonces auprs des offices rgionaux de placement, qui n'ont pas d'emploi et sont immdiatement disponibles en vue d'un placement. Peu importe qu'elles touchent, ou non, une indemnit de chmage. (from https://www.amstat.ch/v2/definition.jsp?lang=fr)

It is in these individuals we are interested.

Next we add the unemployment rate ('Taux de chmage') and the number of registered unemployed individuals ('Demandeurs d'emploi') to the dataframe

In [33]:
#keep the unemployment rate ('Taux de chmage') and convert it to a numerical value
data['unemployment rate'] = list(data.index.str.split(",").str)[2]
data['unemployment rate'] = pd.to_numeric(data['unemployment rate'].str.replace('"', ''))

#keep the number of registered unemployed individuals ('Chmeurs inscrits') and convert it to a numerical value
data['asking unemployed'] = list(data.index.str.split(",").str)[4]
data['asking unemployed'] = pd.to_numeric(data['asking unemployed'].str.replace('"', '').str.replace('\'', ''))

#keep the number of employed individuals looking for a new job ('Demandeurs d'emploi non chmeurs') and convert it to a numerical value
data['asking employed'] = list(data.index.str.split(",").str)[6]
data['asking employed'] = pd.to_numeric(data['asking employed'].str.replace('"', '').str.replace('\'', ''))

#keep the number of  all individuals looking for a new job ('Demandeurs d'emploi') and convert it to a numerical value
data['asking all'] = list(data.index.str.split(",").str)[5]
data['asking all'] = pd.to_numeric(data['asking all'].str.replace('"', '').str.replace('\'', ''))

From the definition of amstat, the number of active individuals is the number individuals looking for a job divided by the unemployment rate, times 100.

The registered unemployment rate can then be obtained by dividing the number of registered unemployed individuals ('Chmeurs inscrits') by the number of active individuals, times 100.

In [34]:
#compute the number of individuals in the active population
data['active'] = (data['asking all']/data['unemployment rate']) * 100

#compute the registered unemployment rate 
data['asking unemployed rate'] = list(data.index.str.split(",").str)[4]
data['asking unemployed rate'] = pd.to_numeric(data['asking unemployed rate'].str.replace('"', '').str.replace("'",''))/(data['active'])*100

data.reset_index(drop=True,inplace=True)

Observations¶

This map and the previous one are not exactly the same, but they are very similar. In all cantons, the "unemployment rate" is now lower (of the order of 0.5% - 2%), since for all active population, less individuals were taken into account (i.e. only the unemployed individuals looking for a job, and not the ones which already have a job). The global trend is still the same though, with Romandy having a higher unemployment rate than the German-speaking part of Switzerland on average.

3 - Unemployment rate in Switzerland: Swiss vs foreign workers¶

[source: amstat]

Now we repeat the exercise for Switzerland but distinguishing Swiss workers from foreign ones.

The Economic Secretary (SECO) releases a monthly report on the state of the employment market. In the latest report (September 2017), it is noted that there is a discrepancy between the unemployment rates for foreign (5.1%) and Swiss (2.2%) workers.

3.1 - Difference in unemployment on two maps¶

Observations¶

As a global trend, we see that the unemployment rate for both Swiss and foreigners is still prevalent in Romandy.

On average though, the unemployment rate among foreigners is much higher than among the Swiss, and this for every single canton. This suggests there is a positive bias toward the Swiss and a negative one toward foreigners when it comes to hiring.

Half of the foreigners are Italian (~15.6%), Germans (~14.9%), Portuguese (~13.2) or French (~6.3%). Italians tend to live in the canton of Ticino, Portuguese in Romandy and in the east of the canton of Grisons and French mostly in Romandy - cantons which are marked with colours of the right-side of the scale (except for the canton of Grisons). If there are more foreigners living in these parts of Switzerland, we could also expect the unemployment rate of foreigners to be higher than in regions with fewer of them.

The trend is less visible for the German population however, which mostly lives in the German-speaking part of Switzerland. In fact, for the German-speaking part of Switzerland, the difference in unemployment rate between foreigners and Swiss may be also due to foreigners tending to not be fluent enough in German or Swiss German, thus lowering their chance of finding a job recruted in this region. In general though, this is not a problem for Germans working in Switzerland.

(statistics taken from https://www.sem.admin.ch/sem/fr/home/aktuell/news/2017/2017-07-17.html#moreinfos-tab-0)

3.2 - Difference in unemployment on one map¶

Approach 1: bivariate choropleth map try #1¶

We will first try to create a map which displays both the foreigners and Swiss unemployment rates by superimposing two colour scales.

In [47]:
data_difference = data_concat.copy()
data_difference.head()
Out[47]:
id canton foreigners swiss
0 AR Appenzell Rhodes-Extrieures 3.4 1.4
1 AI Appenzell Rhodes-Intrieures 2.0 0.5
2 AG Argovie 5.6 2.1
3 BE Berne 5.5 1.8
4 BL Ble-Campagne 4.8 2.2

We find the quartiles for both the foreigners unemployment rate and the Swiss unemployment rate in order to establish a scale for the two populations.

In [48]:
scale_swiss = list(data_difference['swiss'].quantile([x * 1/5 for x in range(1, 5)]).values)
scale_swiss = [math.floor(data_difference['swiss'].min())] + scale_swiss + [math.ceil(data_difference['swiss'].max())]

scale_foreigners = list(data_difference['foreigners'].quantile([x * 1/5 for x in range(1, 5)]).values)
scale_foreigners = [math.floor(data_difference['foreigners'].min())] + scale_foreigners + [math.ceil(data_difference['foreigners'].max())]

The following map has now two different colour scales, which are supposed to be superimposed in some meaningful way:

  • If a canton has a dominant purple colour, then the Swiss unemployment rate is here at its largest, and the foreigners unemployment rate at the lowest.
  • Inversely, if a canton has a dominant blue colour, then the foreigners unemployment rate is here at its largest, and the Swiss unemployment rate at its lowest.
  • If the the dominant colour is some shade of violet - that is, a mix of purple and blue - then this means the foreigners and Swiss unemployment rate are similar, and the higher the darker the purple
In [49]:
map_swiss_foreigners_difference = folium.Map(location=switzerland_center_coord, tiles='cartodbpositron', zoom_start=7)
map_swiss_foreigners_difference.choropleth(geo_data=open(state_geo_path), data=data_difference,
             columns=['id', 'swiss'],
             key_on='id',

             fill_color='PuRd', fill_opacity=0.9, line_opacity=0.2,

map_swiss_foreigners_difference
Out[49]:

We can see there is indeed some trend similar to the one observed on the previous maps. However, this is not an optimal way of representing the difference between foreigners and Swiss unemployment rate, as the opacity of one colour (fill_opacity) can be made arbitrarily small or large with respect to the other, this way completely changing the aspect of the map.

We still kept this map for the sake of showing our approach.

Approach 2: bivariate choropleth map try #2¶

Next we will try to create a bivariate choropleth map without actually mixing the colours, but by assigning to each canton the colour from a matrix of colour, which only symbolizes the mixing of colours.

For this, we find the terciles for both the foreigners unemployment rate and the Swiss unemployment rate, as the matrix we will use is going to be a $3 \times 3$ matrix.

In [50]:
tercile_swiss_1 = list(data_difference['swiss'].sort_values())[int(np.floor(len(data_difference['swiss'])/3))]
tercile_swiss_2 = list(data_difference['swiss'].sort_values())[int(np.floor(len(data_difference['swiss'])*2/3))]

tercile_foreigners_1 = list(data_difference['foreigners'].sort_values())[int(np.floor(len(data_difference['foreigners'])/3))]
tercile_foreigners_2 = list(data_difference['foreigners'].sort_values())[int(np.floor(len(data_difference['foreigners'])*2/3))]

print('swiss:', tercile_swiss_1, tercile_swiss_2)
print('foreigners:', tercile_foreigners_1, tercile_foreigners_2)

swiss: 1.4 2.2
foreigners: 3.9 5.0

We then manually map each canton to a value of the matrix, depending on its foreigners unemployment rate and Swiss unemployment rate.

In [51]:
def non_linear_scale(df):     
    
    if(df['swiss'] < tercile_swiss_1):
        if(df['foreigners'] < tercile_foreigners_1):
            return 1
        elif(tercile_foreigners_1 <= df['foreigners'] and df['foreigners'] < tercile_foreigners_2):
            return 2
        else:
            return 3
    elif(tercile_swiss_1 <= df['swiss'] < tercile_swiss_2):
        if(df['foreigners'] < tercile_foreigners_1):
            return 4
        elif(tercile_foreigners_1 <= df['foreigners'] and df['foreigners'] < tercile_foreigners_2):
            return 5
        else:
            return 6
    else:
        if(df['foreigners'] < tercile_foreigners_1):
            return 7
        elif(tercile_foreigners_1 <= df['foreigners'] and df['foreigners'] < tercile_foreigners_2):
            return 8
        else:
            return 9
In [52]:
data_difference['combined'] = data_difference.apply(non_linear_scale, axis=1)

Now, the foreigners unemployment rate is in almost all cantons considered to be high, except in the canton of Uri and in the canton of Appenzell Innerrhoden (light blue), where it is medium. The unemployment rate is considered to be at the highest for both Swiss and foreigners in the same cantons as before.

In cantons such as the canton of Grison, the canton of Schwyz, the canton of Nidwalden of the canton of Obwalden, the trend for foreigners is completely inverted. The previous map indicated the foreigners unemployment rates were relatively low, but now that these rates are directly compared to the Swiss unemployment rates, they are considered to be high.

No cantons appears in the purple shades either, since the foreigners unemployment rate is always greater than the Swiss unemployment rate.

It again requires a bit of work to import the data from the csv file in a clean and nice pandas dataframe. We will:

  • drop the header
  • remove any kind of quotation marks
  • drop the rows indicating the 'Total' number of unemployed individuals
  • replace entries written in french by an english equivalent
  • add a column indicating the canton code
In [64]:
data = dataCSV.copy()

#drop the header
data = data.iloc[2:-1]

#keep the canton
data['canton'] = list(data.index.str.split(",").str)[0]

#keep the nationality, but drop the 'Total' rows
data['nationality'] = list(data.index.str.split(",").str)[1]
data['nationality'] = data['nationality'].str.replace('"', '')
data['nationality'] = data['nationality'].str.replace('Suisses', 'swiss')
data['nationality'] = data['nationality'].str.replace('Etrangers', 'foreigners')
data = data[data['nationality'] != 'Total']

#keep the age group, but drop the 'Yotal' rows
data['age group'] = list(data.index.str.split(",").str)[2]
data['age group'] = data['age group'].str.replace('"', '')
data = data[data['age group'] != 'Total']
data['age group'] = pd.to_numeric(data['age group'])

#keep th number of unemplyed individuals
data['number of unemployed'] = list(data.index.str.split(",").str)[5]
data['number of unemployed'] = data['number of unemployed'].str.replace('"', '')
data['number of unemployed'] = data['number of unemployed'].str.replace('\'', '')
data['number of unemployed'] = pd.to_numeric(data['number of unemployed'])

data.reset_index(drop=True,inplace=True)

data['id'] = data['canton'].map(amstat_canton_code_mapping)

def plot_clustered_stacked(df_all, title, labels):
    """Given a list of dataframes, with identical columns and index, create a clustered stacked bar plot. 
labels is a list of the names of the dataframe, used for the legend
title is a string for the title of the plot
"""
    
    n_df = len(df_all)
    n_col = len(df_all[0].columns) 
    n_ind = len(df_all[0].index)
    
    ax = plt.subplot(111)
    
    #plot each dataframe
    for df in df_all: 
        ax = df.plot(kind='bar',
                      linewidth=1.,
                      edgecolor='#e0e0e0',
                      color=['#a6cee3', '#1f78b4', '#b2df8a'],
                      stacked=True,
                      ax=ax,
                      legend=False,
                      grid=False,
                      figsize=(18,8),
                      )
        
    #position the bars    
    H="/"
    h,l = ax.get_legend_handles_labels() 
    for i in range(0, n_df * n_col, n_col): 
        for j, pa in enumerate(h[i:i+n_col]):
            for rect in pa.patches: 
                rect.set_x(rect.get_x() + 1 / float(n_df + 1) * i / float(n_col))
                rect.set_width(1 / float(n_df + 1))
                rect.set_hatch(H * int(i / n_col))
               
                
    ax.set_xticks((np.arange(0, 2 * n_ind, 2) + 1 / float(n_df + 1)) / 2.)
    ax.set_xticklabels(df.index, rotation = 90)
    
    ax.set_xlabel('canton')
    ax.set_ylabel('number of unemployed')
    ax.set_title(title)
    
    n=[]        
    for i in range(n_df):
        n.append(ax.bar(0, 0, color="gray", hatch=H * i))


    #add the legend
    legend_1 = ax.legend(h[:n_col], l[:n_col], loc=[1.01, 0.5])
    if labels is not None:
        legend_2 = plt.legend(n, labels, loc=[1.01, 0.1]) 
    ax.add_artist(legend_1)
   
    return ax

#thank you https://stackoverflow.com/questions/22787209/how-to-have-clusters-of-stacked-bars-with-python-pandas

column_names = ['15-24 year', '25-49 year', '>50 year']

df_swiss = pd.DataFrame(table_swiss.values,
                   index=sorted(data['canton'].unique()),
                   columns=column_names)

                   index=sorted(data['canton'].unique()),
                   columns=column_names)

                       'Number of unemployed foreigners and Swiss per age group',
                       ['Swiss', 'foreigners']);

Observations¶

This bar plot shows the number of unemployed foreigners and Swiss per age group and per canton. These are absolute numbers, and we see that, although the unemployment rate is higher among the foreign population, the number of unemployed foreigners is in most cantons actually lower than the number of unemployed Swiss.

In overall, the proportion of unemployed foreigners or Swiss for the different age groups is similar across all cantons: most unemployed individuals are between 25 and 49 years old, followed by the individuals more than 50 years old. The minority of unemployed individuals is between 15 and 24 years old.

Next, we sort the cantons according to the language: we make one group out of French-speaking cantons, and another one out of German-, Italian- and Romansh-speaking cantons.

In [70]:
romandy_cantons = ['FR','GE', 'JU', 'NE', 'VD', 'VS']
roesti_cantons = ['AG', 'AR', 'AI', 'BE', 'BL', 'BS', 'GL', 'GR', 'LU', 'OW',
                  'NW', 'SG', 'SH', 'SO', 'SZ', 'TG', 'TI', 'UR', 'ZG', 'ZH']

We can now compute the total number of unemployed individuals (according to the Swiss Confederation definition of unemployment, that is, including the ones who already have a job) for both the French-speaking part of Switzerland and the German-speaking part of Switzerland, by summing the number of individuals looking for a job over the corresponding cantons.

In the same way, we also compute the total number of active individuals, as it will be used to compute the unemployment rate.

In [71]:
romandy_asking_total = data[data['id'].isin(romandy_cantons)]['asking all'].sum()
romandy_active_total = data[data['id'].isin(romandy_cantons)]['active'].sum()

roesti_asking_total = data[data['id'].isin(roesti_cantons)]['asking all'].sum()
roesti_active_total = data[data['id'].isin(roesti_cantons)]['active'].sum()

For both parts of Switzerland, the unemployment rate can then be obtained by dividing the total number of unemployed individuals by the total number of active individuals.

In [72]:
romandy_asking_rate = romandy_asking_total/romandy_active_total * 100
roesti_asking_rate = roesti_asking_total/roesti_active_total * 100

print('Unemployed rate in the French-speaking part of Switzerland: {0:.4f} %'.format(romandy_asking_rate))
print('Unemployed rate in the German-speaking part of Switzerland: {0:.4f} %'.format(roesti_asking_rate))

Unemployed rate in the French-speaking part of Switzerland: 3.9796 %
Unemployed rate in the German-speaking part of Switzerland: 2.5037 %

These values confirm what we previously observed on the maps: the unemployment rate is in overall higher in the French-speaking part of Switzerland than in the German-speaking part of Switzerland.
